        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Hinged Steel Belt Conveyors</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Hinged Steel Belt Conveyors</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Hinged Steel Belt Conveyors
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A hinged steel belt conveyor uses interlocking steel plates connected by hinge pins to form a continuous, rugged conveying surface for metal chips, stampings, scrap, and heavy industrial debris. The overlapping plate design creates a solid belt that withstands hot materials up to 900&deg;F, resists cutting oil and coolant, and handles sharp-edged scrap that would slice rubber or plastic belts. Hinged steel belt conveyors are the standard chip and scrap removal system in CNC machining centers, stamping presses, laser cutters, and metalworking shops worldwide.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- How It Works -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="how-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Construction</div>
      <h2 id="how-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        How Hinged Steel <span class="text-accent">Belts Work</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Hinged steel belt construction begins with individual steel plates stamped from sheet steel (typically 10-16 gauge). Each plate has a formed hinge along one edge and a mating lip along the opposite edge. Hinge pins pass through the hinge barrels of adjacent plates, linking them into a continuous chain-like belt. The plates overlap when the belt runs on the flat carrying surface and separate slightly as the belt wraps around the head and tail sprockets.</p>

        <p>The belt rides on side rails or wear strips inside a formed steel trough. Drive sprockets at the discharge end engage the hinge pins or side chains to pull the belt forward. A gravity or spring take-up at the tail end maintains belt tension. The belt's top (carrying) run transports material from the loading point to the discharge, where it wraps around the head sprocket and material falls by gravity into a bin, hopper, or secondary conveyor.</p>

        <p>The return run travels below the carrying run inside the same trough. This enclosed design keeps chips, coolant, and debris contained. Some designs include a coolant collection trough beneath the return run that channels cutting fluid back to the machine's coolant tank for recirculation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Belt Types -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="types-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Belt Configurations</div>
      <h2 id="types-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Hinged Belt <span class="text-accent">Types</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Standard Hinged Belt</h3>
        <p>Standard hinged belts use flat overlapping plates with simple hinge-pin connections. They handle most chip types including turnings, borings, and small stampings. Plate widths range from 6" to 48". Standard belts suit light to medium-duty applications at CNC lathes, mills, and drill presses. Mayfran, Jorgensen, and LNS manufacture standard hinged steel belt conveyors for machine tool integration.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Heavy-Duty Hinged Belt</h3>
        <p>Heavy-duty hinged belts use thicker plates (10-12 gauge vs. 14-16 gauge standard), hardened hinge pins, and reinforced side chains. They handle large stamping scrap, die-cast runners, heavy turnings from large-diameter bar stock, and forging flash. Load capacities reach 500-1,000+ lbs per linear foot. Heavy-duty belts serve stamping press lines, large CNC turning centers, and foundry operations.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Perforated Hinged Belt</h3>
        <p>Perforated hinged belts have holes punched in each plate to allow coolant drainage while still conveying chips. The perforations let cutting fluid pass through the belt into the collection trough below rather than being carried to the discharge point. Perforated belts are standard on wet machining applications where coolant recovery is important. Perforation size must be smaller than the smallest chip to prevent fine swarf from passing through.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Magnetic Hinged Belt</h3>
        <p>Magnetic hinged belts incorporate permanent magnets beneath the carrying surface to hold ferrous chips and small parts against the belt on incline sections. Magnets prevent fine chips from sliding backward on steep inclines and eliminate the need for <a href="/conveyor-types/cleated-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cleats</a>. Magnetic belts handle inclines up to 60 degrees for ferrous materials. They do not work with non-ferrous metals (aluminum, brass, stainless steel).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="compare-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Comparison</div>
