            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">Cost is relative within chip/scrap conveyor category. See <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for pricing factors.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Hinged Steel Belt <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">CNC machine chip removal:</strong> The primary application. Hinged steel belts sit beneath CNC lathes, machining centers, and grinders to collect and convey metal chips from the cutting zone to a chip bin. The belt handles all chip morphologies: continuous turnings from lathes, broken chips from mills, and fine swarf from grinders. Mayfran, Jorgensen, LNS, and Hennig are leading chip conveyor manufacturers that integrate directly with major CNC machine brands.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Stamping press scrap:</strong> Hinged steel belts remove blanking slugs, trim scrap, and skeleton scrap from stamping presses. The belt sits in a pit beneath the press or at floor level behind the press, receiving scrap as it falls from the die. Heavy-duty belts handle the impact loading of large slugs dropping from progressive and transfer dies. Multiple presses feed a common trunk-line hinged belt conveyor that delivers all scrap to a central collection point.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Laser and plasma cutting:</strong> Hinged belts collect cut parts, slugs, and dross from laser cutting tables and plasma cutters. The belt handles hot dross particles and sharp cut edges without damage. Some configurations position the belt below the cutting table's slat support system to catch falling parts and scrap simultaneously.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Die casting and foundry:</strong> Hinged steel belts transport hot die-cast parts, runners, gates, and flash from die-cast machines and trim presses. The belt withstands the 600-900&deg;F temperatures of freshly cast aluminum and zinc parts. Coolant spray sections along the belt path cool parts during transport.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Parts transfer:</strong> Beyond scrap, hinged steel belts transport finished parts between operations in metalworking plants. The rugged steel surface handles heavy, sharp, and oily parts that would damage rubber or plastic belts. Parts ride from one machine to the next for multi-operation processing.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Coolant filtration systems:</strong> Hinged steel belts integrated with coolant tanks filter chips from cutting fluid. The belt lifts chips out of the coolant while fluid drains through the perforated belt back into the clean tank. This replaces standalone coolant filtration systems on machines with moderate chip volumes.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Sizing & Selection -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="sizing-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Specification</div>
      <h2 id="sizing-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Sizing & <span class="text-accent">Selection</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt Width</h3>
        <p>Belt width must accommodate the chip discharge area of the machine tool. Standard widths: 6", 8", 10", 12", 15", 18", 24", 30", 36", and 48". For stamping press scrap, belt width must exceed the die width to catch all falling scrap. For CNC machines, the machine manufacturer's chip conveyor opening dimension determines the required belt width.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Belt Speed</h3>
        <p>Hinged steel belt speeds typically range from 10 to 30 FPM. Slower speeds (10-15 FPM) suit continuous chip removal where a steady trickle of chips falls onto the belt. Faster speeds (20-30 FPM) suit batch discharge from stamping presses where large volumes of scrap fall at once. Variable-speed drives allow the belt to run faster during heavy chip production and slower during light cuts.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Discharge Height</h3>
        <p>The discharge end of the belt inclines to dump material into a collection bin. Standard discharge heights range from 30" to 60" above floor level. Higher discharge requires a steeper incline angle, which may need magnetic assist for ferrous materials or <a href="/conveyor-types/cleated-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">cleated belt</a> features. Discharge height should clear the top of the collection bin plus 6-12 inches for material piling.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Material Selection</h3>
        <p>Carbon steel plates are standard and handle most metalworking applications. Stainless steel plates (304 or 316) serve applications with corrosive coolants, stainless steel machining, or food-adjacent manufacturing. See our <a href="/conveyor-types/stainless-steel-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">stainless steel conveyor guide</a> for alloy selection guidance. Hardened plates extend life in abrasive scrap applications but cost more.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Maintenance -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="maint-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Maintenance</div>
      <h2 id="maint-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Maintenance <span class="text-accent">Guide</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Daily:</strong> Check for chip jams at the discharge point and hinge pin area. Remove stringy turnings that wrap around the head sprocket. Verify coolant drainage is unobstructed. Inspect the belt for obvious plate damage or missing plates.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Weekly:</strong> Inspect hinge pins for excessive wear. Check belt tracking and alignment. Verify the take-up mechanism maintains proper tension. Clean the coolant return trough of sludge and fine chip accumulation.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Monthly:</strong> Measure chain elongation to predict replacement timing. Lubricate the drive gearbox per manufacturer specifications. Inspect sprocket teeth for wear patterns that indicate misalignment. Check motor amperage against baseline to detect increasing friction or overloading.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Belt replacement:</strong> Individual damaged plates can be replaced by removing the hinge pins on either side, sliding out the damaged plate, and inserting a replacement. This field-serviceable design is a major advantage over <a href="/conveyor-types/wire-mesh-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">wire mesh belts</a> that require full belt replacement when damaged. Full belt replacement every 5-15 years is typical depending on application severity and maintenance quality.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Belt life range of 5-15 years against Mayfran/Jorgensen published data -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
